# PowerShell + Husky Compatibility

Husky git hooks use `#!/bin/sh` shebangs that PowerShell on Windows cannot execute natively.
This causes `spawn UNKNOWN` or `command not found` errors on `git commit` and `git push`.

## Detection

Before any `git commit` or `git push`, check the shell environment:

```bash
echo $PSVersionTable 2>$null
```

If the output contains `PSVersion` (or the OS info from the user says "Windows" / "powershell"),
the agent is running in PowerShell.

Alternatively, check the OS from the user info metadata — if `Shell: powershell` or `OS Version: Windows`,
apply the PowerShell path.

## When PowerShell is detected

Add `--no-verify` to **both** `git commit` and `git push` commands:

```powershell
git commit --no-verify -m "message"
git push --no-verify origin branch-name
```

**Why this is safe for our workflow:**
- Pre-commit hook runs `npx tsc --noEmit` (type-check)
- Commit-msg hook runs `commitlint` (conventional commit format)
- Pre-push hook runs `npm run lint`
- All three checks also run in CI on every PR — nothing reaches `dev` without passing them
- Skipping locally on PowerShell avoids a blocking error while CI still catches issues

## When PowerShell is NOT detected (macOS / Linux / Git Bash)

Use normal git commands **without** `--no-verify`. Hooks run as expected.

## Preferred long-term fix

If the PM wants hooks to work natively on Windows, suggest configuring Git to use Git Bash for hooks:

```powershell
git config core.hooksPath .husky
git config core.shell "C:/Program Files/Git/bin/sh.exe"
```

This is optional and should only be suggested if the PM asks about it.
